{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487072","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487072"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:56:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:56:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"246"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17582505","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17582505"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T06:45:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T06:45:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"246"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"246","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/246"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.03,0.09,0.06,0.74]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"246"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96628"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"246","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/246"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"246"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79262"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"279"},{"type":"tags","id":"426"},{"type":"tags","id":"1184"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"2040"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"3501"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"10401"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10865"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33127"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96628","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96628"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-day history of intermittent tingling in her left hand. She reports that six months ago she experienced two days of intermittent flashes in the left eye with associated blurriness and pain. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She smokes five cigarettes a day and has no known family history of medical illness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is weakness in the movements of her left hand including wrist flexion/extension and finger abduction. Her visual acuity is 6/12 (right), 6/9-1 (left). Her fundoscopic examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying pathologic process?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ischaemic stroke from embolus","Neuromuscular junction disorder","Hemiplegic migraine","Rapidly progressive neurodegeneration","Autoimmune demyelinating disorder"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with neurological symptoms separated in time (eye symptoms six months ago, hand symptoms now) and space (visual system and motor system), which is highly suggestive of an \u003Cstrong\u003Eautoimmune demyelinating disorder\u003C/strong\u003E, most likely multiple sclerosis (MS). The history of visual disturbances with pain is classic for optic neuritis, a common presenting feature of MS. The current presentation of sensory symptoms (tingling) and motor weakness in the hand represents a new relapse affecting a different part of the central nervous system. This pattern fulfils the McDonald criteria for MS diagnosis, which requires evidence of dissemination in time and space.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIschaemic stroke from embolus\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with sudden onset of focal neurological deficits that remain constant rather than intermittent. While this patient\u0027s smoking is a risk factor, her young age and the episodic nature of symptoms separated by months make stroke less likely. Additionally, strokes do not typically cause visual symptoms like flashing lights, which are more characteristic of optic neuritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeuromuscular junction disorder\u003C/strong\u003E such as myasthenia gravis typically presents with fatigable weakness, often affecting ocular and bulbar muscles first. Pure sensory symptoms like tingling would not be expected, and visual disturbances in myasthenia would manifest as diplopia or ptosis rather than flashing lights and blurred vision.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHemiplegic migraine\u003C/strong\u003E can cause temporary weakness on one side of the body along with visual aura. However, the absence of headache, the persistence of weakness on examination, and the separation of episodes by months rather than hours to days make this diagnosis less likely. Hemiplegic migraine also typically has a strong family history, which is absent here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERapidly progressive neurodegeneration\u003C/strong\u003E such as motor neurone disease would present with progressive, not relapsing-remitting, symptoms. These conditions typically do not affect sensory pathways or cause visual disturbances like those described. The episodic nature of this patient\u0027s symptoms with periods of apparent recovery is inconsistent with a neurodegenerative process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe next step in management would be to arrange an MRI of the brain and spinal cord to look for demyelinating lesions, along with other investigations such as lumbar puncture to look for oligoclonal bands, and visual evoked potentials to confirm optic nerve involvement. Early diagnosis and treatment with disease-modifying therapies can significantly improve long-term outcomes in multiple sclerosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Multiple sclerosis typically presents with episodes of neurological dysfunction separated in time and space, including sensory disturbances, motor weakness, and optic neuritis.","Optic neuritis presents with visual disturbances, eye pain, and may show temporal pallor on fundoscopy, though fundoscopic examination can be normal in the recovery phase.","The McDonald criteria for multiple sclerosis diagnosis requires evidence of dissemination in time and space, with MRI being the gold standard investigation."],"references":["Miller DH, Weinshenker BG, Filippi M, et al. Differential diagnosis of suspected multiple sclerosis: a consensus approach. Multiple Sclerosis. 2008; 14:1157-74. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37479377/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79262"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"246"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79262","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79262"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-02T14:27:08+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-02T14:27:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"246"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96628"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","i